{"title_page": "Erik van Lieshout", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Erik van Lieshout\n| image         = Erik van Lieshout - IFFR-1.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Erik van Lieshout at the [[International Film Festival Rotterdam]]\n| birth_name    = Erik Gerardus Franciscus van Lieshout\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|01|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Deurne, North Brabant|Deurne]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Dutch\n| spouse        = \n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = Heineken Prize\n| elected       = \n| website       = {{URL|erikvanlieshout.com}}\n| bgcolour      = \n}}\n'''Erik Gerardus Franciscus van Lieshout''' is a Dutch contemporary artist most widely known for his installations.\n<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/jan/10/erik-van-lieshout-how-help</ref>\n<ref>http://www.walkerart.org/collections/artists/erik-van-lieshout</ref>\n<ref>http://www.artnet.com/artists/erik%20van-lieshout/</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.massmoca.org/event_details.php?id=146 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815232315/http://www.massmoca.org/event_details.php?id=146 |archive-date=2012-08-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/31/arts/design/31dutc.html</ref> In 2018, he won the Heineken Prize for Art. \n\n== Biography ==\nVan Lieshout was born in [[Deurne, Netherlands|Deurne]] in the Netherlands and worked in [[New York City|New York]], [[Berlin]], [[Cologne]] and [[Rotterdam]]. He studied at the [[Academy of Art and Design St. Joost]] in [[Breda]] from 1987 to 1990 and at [[Ateliers '63]] in [[Haarlem]] from 1990 to 1992. In 1999 he won 2nd prize in the category visual arts of the [[Prix de Rome (Netherlands)|Prix the Rome]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/124948|title=Erik van Lieshout entry at RKD Artists|last=|first=|date=1999-01-08|website=www.rkd.nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Heineken Prizes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lieshout, Erik van}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch installation artists]]\n[[Category:Dutch contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from Deurne, Netherlands]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Erik van Lieshout\n| image         = Erik van Lieshout - IFFR-1.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Erik van Lieshout at the [[International Film Festival Rotterdam]]\n| birth_name    = Erik Gerardus Franciscus van Lieshout\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|01|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Deurne, North Brabant|Deurne]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Dutch\n| spouse        = \n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = Heineken Prize\n| elected       = \n| website       = {{URL|erikvanlieshout.com}}\n| bgcolour      = \n}}\n'''Erik Gerardus Franciscus van Lieshout''' is a Dutch contemporary artist most widely known for his installations.\n<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2011/jan/10/erik-van-lieshout-how-help</ref>\n<ref>http://www.walkerart.org/collections/artists/erik-van-lieshout</ref>\n<ref>http://www.artnet.com/artists/erik%20van-lieshout/</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.massmoca.org/event_details.php?id=146 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815232315/http://www.massmoca.org/event_details.php?id=146 |archive-date=2012-08-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/31/arts/design/31dutc.html</ref> In 2018, he won the Heineken Prize for Art. \n\n== Biography ==\nVan Lieshout was born in [[Deurne, Netherlands|Deurne]] in the Netherlands and worked in [[New York City|New York]], [[Berlin]], [[Cologne]] and [[Rotterdam]]. He studied at the [[Academy of Art and Design St. Joost]] in [[Breda]] from 1987 to 1990 and at [[Ateliers '63]] in [[Haarlem]] from 1990 to 1992. In 1999 he won 2nd price in the category visual arts of the [[Prix de Rome (Netherlands)|Prix the Rome]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/124948|title=Erik van Lieshout entry at RKD Artists|last=|first=|date=1999-01-08|website=www.rkd.nl|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Heineken Prizes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lieshout, Erik van}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch installation artists]]\n[[Category:Dutch contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from Deurne, Netherlands]]\n\n\n{{Netherlands-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: 2nd price \u2192 2nd prize", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erik_van_Lieshout"}
