{"title_page": "Anna Abdallah", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[Honourable]]\n|name               = Anna Abdallah\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Member of Parliament (Tanzania)|MP]]\n|image              = \n|imagesize          = \n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = \n|office             = [[Ministry of Health (Tanzania)|Minister of Health]]\n|term_start         = 2000\n|term_end           = 2005 \n|president          = [[Benjamin Mkapa]]\n|taoiseach          = \n|predecessor        = \n|successor          = \n|order2             =  \n|office2            = [[Ministry of Works (Tanzania)|Minister of Works]] \n|term_start2        = 1995 \n|term_end2          = 2000 \n|president2         = [[Benjamin Mkapa]] \n|predecessor2       =  \n|successor2         = \n|order3             =  \n|office3            = Minister of State for Regional Administration and Local Government  \n|term_start3        = 1991 \n|term_end3          = 1995 \n|president3         = [[Ali Hassan Mwinyi]] \n|predecessor3       =  \n|successor3         = \n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1940|07|26|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = [[Tanganyika Territory|Tanganyika]]\n|birthname          = \n|nationality        = [[Tanzania]]n\n|party              = [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi|CCM]]\n|spouse             = \n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n|footnotes          = \n|blank1             = \n|data1              = \n}}\n\n'''Anna Margareth Abdallah''' (born 26 July 1940) is a [[Tanzania]]n [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi|CCM]] politician and a special seat [[Member of Parliament (Tanzania)|Member of Parliament]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.go.tz/index.php/members/mpcvs/1028/2010-2015 |title=Member of Parliament CV |date=2010 |publisher=[[Parliament of Tanzania]] |accessdate=14 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415164258/http://parliament.go.tz/index.php/members/mpcvs/1028/2010-2015 |archivedate=15 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nFor her primary education, Abdallah went to both Mtandi Primary School and Loleza Girls Middle School in Mbeya, Tanzania.<ref name=\":2\" /> Abdallah went to Tabora Girls Secondary School for secondary education.<ref name=\":2\" /> Abdallah received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in sociology and housing from the [[University of Missouri|University of Missouri, Columbia]] in the [[United States]] in 1963.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HwqQCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Abetchew+Bayan#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|last=Sheldon|first=Kathleen|date=2016-03-04|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442262935|language=en}}</ref> In 1967, she received a diploma in Home Economics from the [[University of London]] (Queen Elizabeth College) in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>\n{{cite web \n |title=Members Profile >> MP CV \n |publisher=Parliament of Tanzania website \n |url=http://www.parliament.go.tz/bunge/Mp_Cv3.asp?PTerm=2005-2010&fpkey=29&vusername=GUEST%22) \n |accessdate=2007-08-04 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203031506/http://www.parliament.go.tz/bunge/Mp_Cv3.asp?PTerm=2005-2010&fpkey=29&vusername=GUEST%22%29 \n |archivedate=2007-12-03 \n |url-status=dead \n }}\n</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAbdallah is a member of the ruling [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] party. Her experience in government began when she was named as one of the first female district commissioners in 1973.<ref name=\":0\" /> She first became a member of parliament in 1975, when there were only five other women members of parliament.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/feb/09/anna-margareth-abdallah-tanzania-vote-woman-lipstick|title=Anna Margareth Abdallah: 'They say, \"Don't vote for the woman, she wears lipstick\"'|last=Smith|first=David|date=2014-02-09|work=The Observer|access-date=2017-11-13|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> As a qualified nurse,<ref>{{cite news\n |title       = Ex-minister stays tight-lipped over AIDS drug controversy\n |publisher   = This Day\n |date        = 2007-03-08\n |url         = http://www.thisday.co.tz/News/1545.html\n |accessdate  = 2007-08-04\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928002457/http://www.thisday.co.tz/News/1545.html\n |archivedate = 2007-09-28\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> she was the Minister of Health for Tanzania from 2000\u20132005.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Welcome Note by Minister of Health\n |publisher    = United States Embassy in Tanzania\n |date         = 2005-10-10\n |url          = http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/sp_10102005b.html\n |accessdate   = 2007-08-04\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060922225510/http://tanzania.usembassy.gov/sp_10102005b.html\n |archive-date = 2006-09-22\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  | title =ABBOTT TANZANIA RIBBON-CUTTING\n  | publisher =PR Newswire at Forbes.com\n  | date =2007-06-28\n  | url =https://www.forbes.com/prnewswire/feeds/prnewswire/2007/06/28/prnewswire200706281823PR_NEWS_B_MAT_NY_NYPHOT6.html\n  | accessdate =2007-08-04  }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}\n</ref> Other government posts she has held include Minister for Public Works (1995-2000), Minister for Agriculture and Livestock Development (1991), and Minister for Local Government, Community Development, Co-operatives and Marketing and many others.<ref name=\"IDRC\">{{cite web\n |last        = O'Neil\n |first       = Maureen\n |title       = Diseases Without Borders: An Economic Struggle?\n |publisher   = [[International Development Research Centre]]\n |year        = 2003\n |url         = http://www.idrc.ca/en/ev-31855-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html\n |accessdate  = 2007-08-04\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070517150214/http://www.idrc.ca/en/ev-31855-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html\n |archivedate = 2007-05-17\n |url-status     = dead\n}}\n</ref> Abdallah was the first woman chairperson of the committee on Defense and Security.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1983, Abdallah was also given direct oversight of the construction of the new capital in [[Dodoma]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She served as National Chairperson of the [[Union of Tanzanian Women]] from 1994\u20132008.<ref name=\"IDRC\" /><ref name=\":0\" />  Abdallah was also the principal of Buhare College from 1969\u20131973.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAbdallah was important in the foundation of [[Mazimbu Graves|Mazimbu]], which would later house a school, called [[Solomon Mahlangu Freedom College]]. At the Mazimbu's establishment, Abdallah planted a \"friendship\" tree and drove to the sight on occasion. She made it a priority to have Mazimbu known as a place that was internationally recognized, placing it on the world map everywhere she went.<ref name=\"Sellstr\u00f6m\">{{Cite book|title=Liberation in Southern Africa \u2013 Regional and Swedish Voices|last=Sellstr\u00f6m|first=Tor|publisher=Elanders Gotab|year=2002|isbn=91-7106-438-9|location=Stockholm|pages=145}}</ref> Abdallah became an unofficial ambassador for the [[African National Congress|ANC]], a national liberation movement, because she'd championed for its cause and spread knowledge about its existence.<ref name=\"Sellstr\u00f6m\"/> During Abdallah's time in the Ministry of Home Affairs, she approved of more land being utilized in Dakawa (unused land in Tanzania) for the purpose of creating more space for the [[African National Congress|ANC]] people who had no educational connection to the institution being built in Mazimbu.<ref name=\"Sellstr\u00f6m\"/>\n\nIn 1991, she inspired the launch of the Creators of Peace (CoP) global peacemakers network at the [[Initiatives of Change]] [[Caux Palace Hotel|conference centre in Caux]], Switzerland, urging the participants and everyone to \u201ccreate peace wherever we are, in our hearts, our homes, our workplace and our community. We all pretend that someone else is the stumbling block\u2026 Could that someone be myself?\u201d<ref name=\"COP\" /> CoP has since been active in many countries, particularly in Africa (South Africa, Burundi, Kenya, Rwanda, Uganda, South Sudan, Sudan, Cameroon, Nigeria, and Tanzania).<ref name=\"COP\">{{cite web\n |last        =  \n |first       =   \n |title       = Creators of Peace\n |publisher   = [[Initiatives of  Change]]\n |year        = 2015\n |url         = http://www.iofcafrica.org/en/creators-of-peace\n |accessdate  = 2017-10-09\n |df          = \n}}</ref><ref name=\"FAC\">{{cite web\n |last        = Lean\n |first       = Mary\n |title       = Diseases Without Borders: An Economic Struggle?\n |publisher   = [[International Development Research Centre]]\n |year        = 2015\n |url         = http://changemakersmagazine.org/creating-peace-wherever-you-are/\n |accessdate  = 2017-10-09\n |df          = \n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, she was awarded the Order of the United Republic of Tanzania.<ref name=\"IDRC\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdallah, Anna Margareth}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chama Cha Mapinduzi MPs]]\n[[Category:Tanzanian MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Tanzanian women in politics]]\n[[Category:Tabora Girls Secondary School alumni]]\n[[Category:Kivukoni College alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Companions of O. R. Tambo]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n\n\n{{Tanzania-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[Honourable]]\n|name               = Anna Abdallah\n|honorific-suffix   = [[Member of Parliament (Tanzania)|MP]]\n|image              = \n|imagesize          = 