{"title_page": "Chiangrai United F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n|  clubname = Chiangrai United<br> \u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e39\u0e44\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e14\n|  image    = Chiangrai utd.png\n|  image_size = 200\n|  fullname = Chiangrai United Football Club <br> \u0e2a\u0e42\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e1f\u0e38\u0e15\u0e1a\u0e2d\u0e25 \u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e39\u0e44\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e14\n|  nickname = ''[[Xylotrupes gideon|The Beetles]]'' <br> ''(\u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e07\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e49\u0e07\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e20\u0e31\u0e22)''\n| short name= CRUTD\n|  founded  = {{Start date and age|2009}}\n|  ground   = [[Singha Stadium]]<br>[[Chiang Rai Province|Chiang Rai]], [[Thailand]]\n|  capacity = 11,354\n|  chairman = Pawitsarat Tiyapairat\n|chrtitle      = President\n|  mgrtitle = Head Coach\n|  manager  = [[Masami Taki]]\n|  league   = [[Thai League 1]]\n|  season   = [[2019 Thai League 1|2019]]\n|  position = [[Thai League 1]], [[2019 Thai League 1|1st]] ''(champions)''\n| website     = https://www.crutd.com/\n| pattern_la1 = _black hoop\n| pattern_b1  = _vneckblack\n| pattern_ra1 = _black hoop\n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = f2773a\n| body1       = f2773a\n| rightarm1   = f2773a\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| socks1      = f2773a\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = FFFFFF\n| socks2 = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la3 = _bw border\n| pattern_b3 = _blackcollar\n| pattern_ra3 = _bw border\n| pattern_sh3 = \n| pattern_so3 = \n| leftarm3 = fa882d\n| body3 = fa882d\n| rightarm3 = fa882d\n| shorts3 = FFFFFF\n| socks3 = fa882d\n| current     = \n}}\n\n'''Chiangrai United Football Club''' ([[Thai alphabet|Thai]] : \u0e2a\u0e42\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e1f\u0e38\u0e15\u0e1a\u0e2d\u0e25 \u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e39\u0e44\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e14) is a professional [[association football]] club based in [[Chiang Rai Province]].\n\n==History==\n===First years===\nIn 2009, Chiangrai United joined the new Thai football setup and started at the 3rd level, [[2009 Regional League Division 2 Northern Region]]. Chiangrai duly came out on top come the end of the regular league season, thus claiming their first ever championship and also crowned as the first ever winners of the Regional League Northern Division.\n\nOn winning the championship, Chiangrai entered the [[2009 Regional League Division 2]], an end of season mini-league for all 5 [[Regional League Division 2]] championship winning teams, and finished as runners-up and promoted to [[Thai Division 1 League]].\n\n===Second Division and League 1 Promotion===\nIn 2010, the club finished 3rd in [[Thai Division 1 League]] and first-ever promoted to the top tier [[Thai League 1]].\n\nChiangrai United opened its first youth academies in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.posttoday.com/sports/212123|title=\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e15\u0e39\u0e19\u0e08\u0e38\u0e14\u0e01\u0e33\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e14\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e22\u0e39\u0e44\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Chiangrai United made a deal with Jarken Group<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/business/Fifth-ranked-Chiangrai-United-in-major-revamp-30289089.html|title=Fifth-ranked Chiangrai United in major revamp|work=}}</ref> to the strengthen brand and initiating a holistic marketing strategy which included business development and strengthening management structures to promote a positive image of the Chiangrai United Sport Passions as a brand to make Chiangrai United become professional and sustainable. The strategy for this deal is to design to promote Chaing Rai United to become the big name club in Thailand.\n\n====2017 & 2018 \u2013 FA Cup winners====\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n|  GK_nat = Thailand|  GK = [[Chatchai Budprom|Chatchai]]\n| CB_nat = Thailand|  CB = [[Shinnaphat Lee-Oh|Shinnaphat]]\n| RCB_nat = Thailand|  RCB = [[Pratum Chuthong|Pratum]]\n| LCB_nat = Brazil| LCB = [[Everton Gon\u00e7alves Saturnino|Everton]]\n| RWB_nat = Thailand|  RWB = [[Piyaphon Phanichakul|Piyaphon (C)]]\n| LWB_nat = Thailand|  LWB = [[Suriya Singmui|Suriya]]\n| LCM_nat = Thailand| LCM = [[Phitiwat Sukjitthammakul|Phitiwat]]\n| LCF_nat = Thailand| LCF = [[Sivakorn Tiatrakul|Sivakorn]]\n| RCM_nat = Thailand| RCM = [[Thitipan Puangchan|Thitipan]]\n| RCF_nat = Brazil| RCF = [[Vander Luiz Silva Souza|Vander]]\n| AM_nat = Brazil| AM = [[Felipe Azevedo|Felipe]]\n| caption = [[2017 Thai FA Cup Final]] starting lineup Chiangrai United 4 \u2013 2 [[Bangkok United]]\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/th/match/chiangrai-united-v-bangkok-united/%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%99/ejija8p6ovavf765cwn39q25m |title=Report from goal.com |publisher=Chiangrai United vs Bangkok United. Retrieved 25 November 2017.}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2017, the club continued to make agreements with sponsors to improve the club's professional image and attract [[Tanaboon Kesarat]]. They also secured players such as; [[Vander Luiz Silva Souza|Vander Luiz]], [[Felipe Azevedo]], [[Henrique Andrade Silva|Henrique Silva]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.matichon.co.th/news/347221|title=\u2018\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u2019 \u0e17\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21 300 \u0e25. \u0e21\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07\u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e41\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e35\u0e01-\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e4a\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e43\u0e19 5 \u0e1b\u0e35 \u0e04\u0e48\u0e32\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27 \u2018\u0e18\u0e19\u0e1a\u0e39\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u2019 \u0e44\u0e21\u0e48\u0e16\u0e36\u0e07 50 \u0e25.|work=}}</ref>\n\nUnder Brazilian coach [[Alexandre Gama]] , The Beetles was victorious in the [[2017 Thai FA Cup Final|2017 FA Cup Final]] with [[Bangkok United]]. This proved to be a case of redemption for Chiangrai as winning the first piece of silverware in club-history, three days after losing to [[Muangthong United]] in the League Cup final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chiangrai see off Bangkok to win Thai FA Cup|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/asian-football/749396/chiangrai-see-off-bangkok-win-thai-fa-cup/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the club attract [[Lee Yong-Rae]] and [[Bill (footballer)|Bill]]. \n\nChiangrai defeated the [[2017 Liga 1]] runners-up [[Bali United]] 3\u20132 in a qualifying preliminary round 2 and losing the [[2017 Chinese Super League]] to runners-up [[Shanghai SIPG]] 1\u20130 in a qualifying play-offs round for the [[AFC Champions League]] group stages.\n\nIn [[2018 Thai FA Cup Final|2018 FA Cup Final]], The Beetles weathered certain things [[2018 Thai League 1|Thai League 1]] winners [[Buriram United]] could hurl at them at Supachalasai Stadium to record a 3\u20132 victory, a hat-trick by [[Bill (footballer)|Bill]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chiang Rai United make it two with FA Cup win|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/sports/1565814/chiang-rai-united-make-it-two-with-fa-cup-win}}</ref>\n\n====2019 \u2013 League 1 title====\n{{football squad on pitch|align=left\n|  GK_nat = Thailand|  GK = [[Apirak Woravong|Apirak]]\n| CB_nat = Brazil|  CB = [[Brinner Henrique Santos Souza|Brinner]]\n| RCB_nat = Thailand|  RCB = [[Shinnaphat Leeaoh|Shinnaphat]]\n| LCB_nat = Thailand| LCB = [[Sarawut Inpaen|Sarawut]]\n| RWB_nat = Thailand|  RWB = [[Piyaphon Phanichakul|Piyaphon]]\n| LWB_nat = Thailand|  LWB = [[Suriya Singmui|Suriya]]\n| LCM_nat = Thailand| LCM = [[Phitiwat Sukjitthammakul|Phitiwat (C)]]\n| LW_nat = Thailand| LW = [[Ekanit Panya|Ekanit]]\n| RCM_nat = Thailand| RCM = [[Sivakorn Tiatrakul|Sivakorn]]\n| RW_nat = Brazil| RW = [[William Henrique|William]]\n| CF_nat = Brazil| CF = [[Bill (footballer)|Bill]]\n| caption = Usual starting line-up of the [[2019 Thai League 1|2019 League 1]] winning team<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thaileague.co.th/club-info/?id=131&tn=33 |title=Match Play Chiangrai United Players |publisher=thaileague.co.th |accessdate=26 October 2019 |archive-url=https://www.thaileague.co.th/club-info/?id=131&tn=33 |archive-date=26 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nChiangrai defeated the [[2018 Myanmar National League]] champions [[Yangon United]] 3\u20131 in a qualifying preliminary round 2 and drew the [[2018 J1 League]] runners-up [[Sanfrecce Hiroshima]] in a qualifying play-offs round for the [[AFC Champions League]] group stages; the match finished 0\u20130 after extra time, with Chiangrai losing the penalty shoot out 4\u20133 at [[Hiroshima Big Arch]].\n\nIn October 2019, after announcement of the appointment of [[Ailton dos Santos Silva]] as the new head coach, The Beetles won the [[Thai League 1]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e31\u0e22\u0e41\u0e23\u0e01 ,\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e23\u0e13\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e48\u0e27\u0e07\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e17\u0e49\u0e32\u0e22 : \u0e1a\u0e17\u0e2a\u0e23\u0e38\u0e1b\u0e42\u0e15\u0e42\u0e22\u0e15\u0e49\u0e32 \u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e25\u0e35\u0e01 2019|url=https://www.foxsports.co.th/opinions-and-features/180723/\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e0a\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e4c\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e31\u0e22\u0e41\u0e23\u0e01-\u0e2a\u0e38/}}</ref> Chiangrai United and [[Buriram United F.C.|Buriram United]] ended up with identical 58 points from 30 matches. However, they were declared the winners of the league on the basis of a better head-to-head record, Chiangrai held Buriram to a goalless draw away in the first leg in April then thrashed the northeastern giants 4 to nothing at home in July,<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e44\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e4c\u0e15\u0e31\u0e19 : \u201c\u0e2a\u0e01\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e4c 4-0 \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e23\u0e35\u0e23\u0e31\u0e21\u0e22\u0e4c \u0e04\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u201d|url=https://www.foxsports.co.th/foot-ball/thai-football/156880/\u0e44\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e4c\u0e15\u0e31\u0e19-\u0e2a\u0e01\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e4c-4-0-\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e23\u0e35/}}</ref> Chiangrai United is the third to win the top flight after Buriram and [[Muangthong United F.C.|Muangthong]] since the country's premier tournament was revamped in 2009.\n\nThe side is commented to fare well in most big games, with compactness and discipline springing surprises. Instead of being burdened with keeping possession, they stifled opponents with a rehearsed repertoire of both defensive and pressing moves, topped off with lethal counter-attacks.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e21\u0e34\u0e15\u0e15\u0e34 \u0e15\u0e34\u0e22\u0e30\u0e44\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e0a: \u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22 \u0e22\u0e39\u0e44\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e47\u0e14 \u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e15\u0e19 \u0e1c\u0e39\u0e49\u0e04\u0e19 \u0e41\u0e25\u0e30\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e40\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e07|url=https://waymagazine.org/mitti-chiangrai-united/}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\nThe following are the sponsors of CRUTD (named \"CRUTD Partners\"):\n===Title and Shirt Sponsors===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;margin-left:1em;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:darkorange; color:Black;\"|Period\n!style=\"background:darkorange; color:Black;\"|Kit Manufacturer\n!style=\"background:darkorange; color:Black;\"|Title Sponsor\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Puma (brand)|Puma]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thairath.co.th/sport/thaifootball/1178770|title=\u0e2a\u0e27\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e21! '\u0e01\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e07\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e49\u0e07' \u0e08\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e21\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1e\u0e39\u0e21\u0e48\u0e32 \u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e41\u0e02\u0e48\u0e07\u0e25\u0e38\u0e22\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e25\u0e35\u0e01 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Singha]]\n|-\n|2019\u20142020\n|[[FBT (company)|FBT]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.co.th/foot-ball/thai-football/90514/official-\u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e41\u0e02\u0e48/|title=OFFICIAL : \u0e40\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e22\u0e07\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e41\u0e02\u0e48\u0e07\u0e24\u0e14\u0e39\u0e01\u0e32\u0e25\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Official Sponsors===\n2020 season <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crutd.com/|title=list of Sponsors from Official club website}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Bangkok Airways]]\n* TOA\n* [[Muang Thai Life Assurance]]\n* \u0e3aBGF\n* [[Samart Group|Samart]]\n* [[Toyota]] Chiangrai\n* Overbrook Hospital\n* [[Dairy Farming Promotion Organization of Thailand|DPO]]\n* [[Central Group|Central Plaza]]\n* [[Major Cineplex]]\n* Hornbill Group \n* Thaweeyont\n* [[Nikon]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:Singha Stadium.jpg|thumb|right|Singha Stadium.]]\n''Main articles: [[Singha Stadium]], [[Mae Fah Luang University Stadium]]''\n\nChiangrai United's home ground is the '''United Stadium of Chiangrai''', which has also been known as the '''[[Singha Stadium]] ''' since July 2017 due to sponsorship commitments. The stadium is situated in [[Chiang Rai Province]], [[Thailand]]. The Singha Stadium is near [[Chiang Rai International Airport|Mae Fah Luang International Airport]] and has a capacity of 11, 354 people.\n\n===Locations by season===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Coordinates\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n! Year\n|-\n| {{coord|20.058081|99.895745|format=dms|type:landmark_scale:3000}}\n|  [[Chiang Rai Province|Chiang Rai]]\n| [[Mae Fah Luang University Stadium]]\n| 3,346\n| 2009\u20132012\n|-\n| {{coord|19.956944|99.874722|format=dms|type:landmark_scale:3000}}\n|  [[Chiang Rai Province|Chiang Rai]]\n| [[